7. Create a README for the docs:

docs/README.md

```markdown
# Documentation for Duck Brilliance Pipeline

This directory contains HTML documentation for the Duck Brilliance Pipeline project.

## Quick Start

1. **Generate HTML documentation:**
   ```bash
   python generate_html.py
```

1. Preview locally:
   ```bash
   python deploy_docs.py preview
   ```
2. Build everything:
   ```bash
   python deploy_docs.py all
   ```

Files

· index.html - Main landing page with overview
· pipeline.html - Pipeline main module documentation
· transforms.html - Transform classes reference
· config.html - Configuration system documentation
· validation.html - Validation utilities
· cli.html - Command-line interface guide
· tests.html - Test suite examples
· usage.html - Quick start guide
· generate_html.py - Script to generate HTML from source
· deploy_docs.py - Deployment and preview utilities

Deployment

GitHub Pages

1. Enable GitHub Pages in your repository settings
2. Set source to docs/ folder
3. Push the HTML files
4. Your docs will be available at: https://yourusername.github.io/duck-brilliance-pipeline/

Custom Hosting

1. Copy all HTML files to your web server
2. Ensure proper MIME types for .html files
3. Update links in sitemap.xml if needed

Features

· Syntax Highlighting: Using highlight.js for Python code
· Responsive Design: Works on mobile and desktop
· Copy Code: One-click copy for code examples
· Search Engine Ready: Includes sitemap and meta tags
· Easy Navigation: Consistent navigation across all pages

Customizing

To customize the documentation:

1. Edit the CSS in individual HTML files
2. Modify generate_html.py to change the template
3. Add new pages by creating additional HTML files
4. Update navigation links in all pages

Updating

When you update the source code, regenerate the HTML:

```bash
python generate_html.py
```

This will update all HTML files with the latest source code.

```

## 8. Let's run the generator to create all the HTML files:

```python
# Save this as generate_all_docs.py in the root directory
import subprocess
import sys
import os

def main():
    print("Generating complete documentation...")
    
    # Create docs directory if it doesn't exist
    os.makedirs("docs", exist_ok=True)
    
    # Generate HTML from source files
    print("1. Generating HTML from source code...")
    subprocess.run([sys.executable, "docs/generate_html.py"])
    
    # Create the index page (already created above)
    print("2. Creating main index page...")
    
    # Create transforms page (already created above)
    print("3. Creating transforms reference...")
    
    # Create usage guide (already created above)
    print("4. Creating quick start guide...")
    
    # Create sitemap
    print("5. Creating sitemap...")
    subprocess.run([sys.executable, "docs/deploy_docs.py", "sitemap"])
    
    # Create README for docs
    print("6. Creating documentation README...")
    
    print("\n✅ Documentation generation complete!")
    print("\n📂 Files generated in docs/ directory:")
    print("   - index.html          (Main landing page)")
    print("   - pipeline.html       (Pipeline code)")
    print("   - transforms.html     (Transform reference)")
    print("   - config.html         (Configuration)")
    print("   - validation.html     (Validation)")
    print("   - cli.html            (CLI reference)")
    print("   - tests.html          (Tests)")
    print("   - usage.html          (Quick start)")
    print("   - sitemap.xml         (SEO sitemap)")
    
    print("\n🌐 To preview locally:")
    print("   cd docs && python -m http.server")
    print("   Then open http://localhost:8000")
    
    print("\n🚀 To deploy to GitHub Pages:")
    print("   git add docs/*")
    print("   git commit -m 'Update documentation'")
    print("   git push")
    print("   Enable GitHub Pages in repository settings")

if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()
```

Final Directory Structure:

```
duck-brilliance-pipeline/
├── docs/
│   ├── index.html              # Main landing page
│   ├── pipeline.html           # Pipeline documentation
│   ├── transforms.html         # Transforms reference
│   ├── config.html             # Configuration guide
│   ├── validation.html         # Validation documentation
│   ├── cli.html                # CLI interface guide
│   ├── tests.html              # Test suite examples
│   ├── usage.html              # Quick start guide
│   ├── generate_html.py        # HTML generator script
│   ├── deploy_docs.py          # Deployment utilities
│   ├── generate_all_docs.py    # Complete generation script
│   ├── sitemap.xml             # SEO sitemap
│   └── README.md               # Docs README
├── (rest of your project files)
└── README.md                   # Main project README
```

How to Use:

1. Generate Documentation:
   ```bash
   python docs/generate_all_docs.py
   ```
2. Preview Locally:
   ```bash
   cd docs
   python -m http.server
   # Open http://localhost:8000
   ```
3. Deploy to GitHub Pages:
   · Enable GitHub Pages in your repo settings
   · Set source to /docs folder
   · Push the docs directory

Key Features of the Documentation:

1. Professional Design - Clean, modern interface with gradients and shadows
2. Responsive Layout - Works on mobile, tablet, and desktop
3. Syntax Highlighting - Code blocks with proper Python highlighting
4. Interactive Elements - Copy buttons, smooth scrolling, hover effects
5. Complete Navigation - Easy navigation between all documentation pages
6. SEO Ready - Sitemap, meta tags, and proper structure
7. Auto-generated - Can regenerate from source code automatically
8. Browser Features - Copy code with one click, back-to-top buttons

The documentation now provides a complete, professional web interface for your pipeline that you can share with team members, stakeholders, or publish publicly!